Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men released a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a blank check to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and regard his confirmation as China's lifetime leader later in the year as a simple formality.
After concentrating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his life's dream with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sentimentality.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the dissolution had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise, being aware of his cruelty.
He destroyed the capital of Chechnya, Grozny. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever operator of the KGB, but he seems to have changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers open-armed, but they turned out to be entirely on the same positions as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Ukrainians have put up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems nothing can stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been tricked by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was originally the seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 2014 Euromaidan protests.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The deep-rooted corruption in the awarding of defense contracts also played an important role in his insufficient results.
Yet, rather than blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all rules of war, including bombing civilians indiscriminately.
Many hospitals were hit and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) was damaged.
In the besieged Marioupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia might well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already done wonders by managing to strengthen the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is acting unilaterally.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remain « strong », Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say that he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
